{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618082"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:19:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:19:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16490"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16490"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.06,0.09,0.27,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75905"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9181"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16490"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61418"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5080"},{"type":"tags","id":"5081"},{"type":"tags","id":"9948"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21788"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22175"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75905"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with productive cough and thick sputum due to bronchiectasis. She is prescribed bromhexine to help manage her symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of bromhexine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Breaks down mucopolysaccharide fibres in mucus","Suppresses cough reflex through central nervous system mediation","Stimulates respiratory ciliary beating frequency and coordination","Inhibits mucus production through anticholinergic mechanisms","Causes bronchodilation through beta-2 adrenergic stimulation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreaking down mucopolysaccharide fibres in mucus\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of action of bromhexine. This reduces mucus viscosity and allows for expectoration of thinner respiratory secretions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppressing cough reflex through central nervous system mediation\u003C/strong\u003E: this is the mechanism of antitussive medications like codeine or dextromethorphan, which act centrally to reduce cough. Bromhexine does not have this effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulating respiratory ciliary beating frequency and coordination\u003C/strong\u003E: this mechanism is seen with drugs like erdosteine. While mucus clearance improves with bromhexine, it does not directly affect ciliary function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting mucus production through anticholinergic mechanisms\u003C/strong\u003E: anticholinergic medications reduce mucus production. In contrast, bromhexine increases serous fluid production and breaks down mucopolysaccharide fibres, to decrease mucus viscosity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECausing bronchodilation through beta-2 adrenergic stimulation\u003C/strong\u003E: this is the mechanism of beta-2 agonists and anticholinergics. Bromhexine has no effect on bronchial smooth muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy breaking down mucopolysaccharide fibres and increasing serous fluid production, bromhexine helps thin mucus secretions and facilitate their removal from the respiratory tract.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bromhexine is a mucolytic agent that works by breaking down mucopolysaccharide fibres in mucus.","Bromhexine increases the production of serous fluid and reduces mucus viscosity in the respiratory tract.","The main therapeutic use of bromhexine is to thin and loosen mucus secretions in respiratory conditions."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61418"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16490"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61418"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T13:15:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T13:16:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9181"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75905"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"d